title: For Sale:  Custom 9mm M70a
location: Santa Fe, NM, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
This is one of the modern Zastava (Yugo) M70a 9mm pistols. It is my single favorite one to shoot that I have ever had. Because it is a modern handgun, some modifications have been done to it. If by chance you want to return it to its original appearance, it can be done by reinstalling the factory grips, and just drifting out the sights to replace them. However, I doubt you will want to do much of that once you shoot it. 

 I am a Tokarev freak (among other things, lol) and this one has had a trigger job and its action polished. I have even shimmed the hammer group, which aids in the trigger's crispness. All the polishing below was done by hand, and not with some Dremel tool, by the way. I learned a lot about tuning Toks from this pistol. It has the single best trigger pull of any Tokarev I have ever had. It is light and crisp, and everything I have learned about smithing Toks was put into it. trigger bearing surfaces are polished to 2000 grit. The feedramp was polished to 2000 grit, and the barrel polished to 1500. The magazine safety has been removed, which also helped the trigger, and puts it inline with a 9mm 1911 as far as accuracy and its fighting capabilities are concerned. I have installed a set of polymer 1911 grips on it, and stained them to a desert camouflage coloration. In my photos it looks like the right grip is lighter than the left one. in person this isn't true. they match. the sights not have a bright orange enamel three dot sight picture. I have found it to be superbly accurate and prefer shooting it over my CZ75.

 it was already a great pistol when I got it, but let's face it, they are not known for the smoothest actions or the lightest triggers out of the box. This has been corrected. I shoot empty shotgun shells with it as 25-40 yards, and empty Coke cans at 50-75 now. It has gun grip tape on the front and rear backstraps fitted, and coupled with the checkered 1911 grips, it locks into your hand as well as a Hi Power or a CZ. I suggest you shoot it a bit before removing these. You'll see what I mean. I have never had any sort of a malfunction with it, and partly because of the polished barrel, it feeds anything you put in it, including every hollow point I have feed through it.

 It will come with its original box and sleeve, the factory cleaning brush that is unused, and all the papers. The original Zastava grips are in it. I am also including a European holster of some sort that it fits in, and works well for field use.

 I bought this pistol new about a year and a half ago. I am selling it for less than I paid before spending the money and hours on it. if you get it and don't like it for any reason at all, return it to me undamaged and I will refund your money with no questions asked.

 I can take cash, a USPS Money Order for payment or a discreet online one if you want to use your credit card.


 Thank you for reading my ad.

postcontent:
24 Inch barrel rifle chambered in 25-20 WCF, serial number puts production in 1914.  The 25-20 is the second rarest caliber second only to .218 bee, I believe only about 40,000 were made out of the 1,000,000 or so 1892's, and of those only about 26,000 were rifles. Just got this for a trade, now need the cash.  Action cycles, but needs to be field stripped, and cleaned to fix hammer follow issue, I hit it with some CLP, and that helped, but it needs to be taken apart, and thoroughly cleaned to get the rest of the crud out of the hammer notch, as it stands it cycles fine, but the lever must be thrown with some force to get it to cock, cleaning should fix this, but I am not a gunsmith.  Other than that it's mechanically sound with a nice patina, and near flawless wood from what I can tell, there is a slight dent in the feed tube, but I don't think it should effect function, but I have no ammo to verify this, but if it's a problem the tube can be easily replaced, Numrich has the part for just $11.80, and it's in stock as I type this.  It's a good honest rifle for 100 years old.  I have more pictures for serious inquiries.  As I said I just got this on a trade so that's about all I know, sold as is.

title: For Sale:  Winchester model 1911 semi auto 12 gauge!  very rare to see one in this condition!!!
postcontent:
hello,
What I have for sale is a very rare and very nice Winchester model 1911 12 gauge semi auto shotgun.  It was manufactured in 1912 and all serial nubers match.  I fell into two of these, and I am going to let this one go.  It was winchester's first attempt at a semi auto shotgun and trying to work around John M. Browning's patents of the time!!!  It cocks from the barrel instead of a charging handle.  It was dubbed "the widdow maker" due to a series of accidents caused by poor gun handling techniques.

This firearm has a 5 round capacity and features a 26" full choke barrel.  All original blueing, all original parts!!!  I removed the plug for skeet, but it will be included.  The stock and forend are amazing and are american walnut stained a deep reddish brown.  

I have used this for a couple hundred rounds playing skeet, with zero problems.  You can use factory target loads no problem, do not be stupid and throw high power rounds through it, its 102 years old.  I personally reload shotshells for these.  

This beast is a slayer of clays.  I can show you a video.  Ranging out to 90 yards, will still smash them.  It has never ceased to impress me, and anger the people I shoot against.  You will love this weapon.  I want her to go to a good home.

May be willing to consider trades, for an o/u or something of interest.  I am pricing this at 650 or best offer.  email or text preferred  8 zero 8 three 4 three 9 nine 9 four.  let me know what you got.  If no interest, its going on gun broker.
